The inner gear ring with variable tooth-number, the method of varying the tooth-number, and the variable transmission using the inner gear ring are explained hereinafter in combination with the drawings and the embodiments:
FIG. 1 shows the curled rack composed of the teeth;
FIG. 2 shows the wide teeth at the front section of the rack and the gear ring connecting interfaces on the rack;
FIG. 3 shows the condition that the inner gear ring is coordinated with one tapered disc;
FIGS. 4 (a) and (b) show the conditions that the distance between the two tapered discs are the nearest, the radius of the inner gear ring is the minimum, the distance between the two tapered discs are the farthest, and the radius of the inner gear ring is the maximum respectively;
FIG. 5 is the brief cutaway view of the variable transmission along axial direction;
FIG. 6 is the brief view showing the location relations between the main planetary gear train and the tooth guiding grooved rail, traction rod when the inner gear ring is the maximum;
FIG. 7 is the brief view showing the location relations between the main planetary gear train and the tooth guiding grooved rail, traction rod when the inner gear ring is the minimum;
FIG. 8 shows the relations between the movements and locations of the traction rod, shift driver plates and rack.
FIG. 9 is the schematic view showing the coordination of the inner gear ring composed of two rack sections and the two main planetary gear trains;
FIG. 10 is the brief cutaway view of Embodiment 2 along axial direction;
FIG. 11 is the brief view showing the location relations of the main sun gear, inner planetary gear, outer planetary gear and pinion (P) when the inner gear ring in Embodiment 2 is the maximum;
FIG. 12 is the brief view showing the location relations of the main sun gear, inner planetary gear, outer planetary gear and pinion (P) when the inner gear ring in Embodiment 2 is the minimum;

Suppose the tooth-number of the inner gear ring B is ZB, that of the outer planetary gear 13 is Z13, that of the main sun gear 11 is Z11 and that of the pinions P is ZP, then:
When ZB/Z13 > Z11/ZP, the directions of the input and output rotation are opposite, which are used as the forward shift;
When ZB/Z13 < Z11/ZP, the directions of the input and output rotation are the same, which are used as the reverse shift;
When ZB/Z13=Z11/Zp, the output rotation keeps 0, which is used as brake for locking.

claim.claim-text:
An inner gear ring with variable tooth-number, comprising a pair of tapered discs (7, 8) disposed coaxially and capable of changing their mutual axial distance through relative movement, wherein the inner walls (9) of said two tapered discs (7, 8) are inwardly concave and face each other, and a curled rack (3) composed of several teeth (1), set between the two facing walls of the tapered discs (7, 8), cogs (2) being set on said teeth (1),

wherein the rear section (5) of the rack (3) consists of narrow teeth, the front section (4) of the rack (3) is composed of wide teeth, the two side surfaces of the rack (3) being in close contact with the inner walls (9) of the two tapered discs (7, 8); the inner walls (9) of the two tapered discs are provided with concave faces (10) fit for the wide teeth, thus causing the inner gear ring (B) to maintain a circular ring shape; and the tooth-number of the inner gear ring (B) that the rear section (5) of the rack (3) is in or out of the inner gear ring (B) varies with the change of the relative distance of the two tapered discs (7, 8);

characterized in that: the front section (4) of the rack (3) is provided with gear ring connecting interfaces (A) for the access of the rear section (5) of the rack, the rear section (5) of the rack (3) passing through the connecting interfaces (A) and forming the circular inner gear ring (B), wherein the gear ring connecting interfaces (A) are constituted by the first wide teeth (6) being in the form of an "n" , through which the rear section (5) passes;

the height of the "n"-shaped wide teeth increases from the front end of the rack (3) towards the rear; and

the rear section (5) of the rack passes through the interfaces (A) at a tangent to the inner gear ring (B).

Couronne à denture intérieure à un nombre de dents variable, comprenant une paire de disques coniques (7, 8) disposés coaxialement et capables de changer leur distance axiale mutuelle par un déplacement relatif, dans laquelle les parois intérieures (9) desdits deux disques coniques (7, 8) sont concaves vers l'intérieur et se font mutuellement face, et une crémaillère (3) en boucle composée de plusieurs dents (1), placée entre les deux parois se faisant face des disques coniques (7, 8), des dents de chaîne (2) étant placées sur lesdites dents (1),

dans laquelle la section arrière (5) de la crémaillère (3) comprend des dents étroites, la section avant (4) de la crémaillère (3) est composée de larges dents, les deux surfaces latérales de la crémaillère (3) étant en contact étroit avec les parois intérieures (9) des deux disques coniques (7, 8) ; les parois intérieures (9) des deux disques coniques sont pourvues de faces concaves (10) prévues pour les larges dents, amenant ainsi la couronne à denture intérieure (B) à conserver une forme de couronne circulaire ; et le nombre de dents de la couronne à denture intérieure (B) de la section arrière (5) de la crémaillère (3) qui est dans ou hors de la couronne à denture intérieure (B) varie avec le changement de la distance relative des deux disques coniques (7, 8) ;

caractérisée en ce que : la section avant (4) de la crémaillère (3) est pourvue d'interfaces de liaison de couronne (A) pour l'accès de la section arrière (5) de la crémaillère, la section arrière (5) de la crémaillère (3) passant à travers les interfaces de liaison (A) et formant la couronne à denture intérieure (B) circulaire, dans laquelle les interfaces de liaison (A) de la couronne sont constituées des premières larges dents (6) qui ont la forme d'un « n » à travers lesquelles la section arrière (5) passe ;

la hauteur des larges dents en forme de « n » augmente de l'extrémité avant de la crémaillère (3) vers l'arrière ; et

la section arrière (5) de la crémaillère passe à travers les interfaces (A) tangentiellement à la couronne à denture intérieure (B).
